Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat
oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Remove and discard any large stems from @kale{4%ounce}. Drain and rinse
@chickpeas{1%can}.

Place kale and chickpeas in a large #bowl{}. Toss with @garlic powder{1%tsp}, half
the @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}, a large drizzle of @olive oil{}, and a
pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread kale and chickpeas out in a single layer on a foil-lined #baking sheet{}.
Roast on top rack until slightly crispy, stirring halfway through, ~{18-22%minutes}.
(For 4 servings, divide kale and chickpeas between two baking sheets and roast
on top and middle racks, swapping rack positions halfway through.) Wipe out bowl.

Meanwhile, in a small #pot{} (medium pot for 4 servings), combine
@Israeli couscous{5%ounce}, remaining @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}, and
@water{1 1/4%cups}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook
until tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}.

In bowl used for kale and chickpeas, whisk together @red pepper jam{1%unit},
@red wine vinegar{2 1/2%tsp}, @olive oil{1%tbsp}(all for 4 servings), and a pinch
of @salt{} and @pepper{} until thoroughly combined.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water, then pat dry with paper towels.

Pat @shrimp{10%ounce} dry with paper towels. Season all over with salt and
pepper. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Add shrimp and cook, stirring occasionally, until opaque and cooked through,
~{4-6%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{}.

To bowl with dressing, add tomatoes and @dried apricots{1%ounce}. Toss to combine.

Transfer roasted kale and chickpeas and cooked couscous to bowl. Toss to combine;
season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide kale and chickpea couscous between bowls and top with
@sliced almonds{1/2%ounce}. Serve.

Serve shrimp atop kale and chickpea couscous.

> Shellfish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.